narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned the experimental methods and theory behind different fields of BME through bone biomechanics, biomedical signals/imaging, ECGs, EMGs, and respiration measurements. We learned how to work with a data collection device, analog signal amplifiers, digital filters, and MATLAB data processing.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I liked the one lab every two weeks model!

Switching instructors every two labs was very confusing and made it seem like we had no uniform organization. TAs had no clue what they were doing and there was really no way to get outside help in labs.

I disliked how the lab reports required tedious/mind numbing calculations. I feel like I really missed the point on a lot of labs because the report required specific attention to irrelevant calculations instead of the bigger picture, conceptual learning.

Strengths: The labs were very fun and I loved how we could see how they connect to real-world BME applications! Overall the teaching staff and fellows were extremely responsive and helpful.

Weaknesses: The labs were sometimes quite overwhelming and unclear - a good example is the EMG and respiratory labs. Even when the protocol was followed, sometimes the data would not be clear and would be very hard to analyze, which made completing the lab reports difficult. Addtionally, for the respiratory lab, the questions in the lab report were quite unclear which resulted in many points being deducted due to misinterpretation of the questions.

i love that it's on a bi-weekly schedule for the most part. one of the only courses that is actually .5-- but STILL difficult at times 

the labs were often confusing with unclear instructions and unclear lab report expectations

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: This is one of the required lab courses for BME but it's a great one! The workload per lab is pretty high but you end up only meeting about once every two weeks, which made the workload very manageable.
